Good morning,

Today's Stratechery Interview is with Jon Yu. Jon is the man behind Asianom=
etry ( https://www.youtube.com/@Asianometry ) , one of the best tech YouTub=
e channels in the world. Jon is very curious about technology =E2=80=94 and=
 a whole bunch of other topics, particularly in Asia =E2=80=94 and does int=
ense research and shares what he learns through narrated YouTube videos.

I also just announced that Asianometry is joining the Stratechery Plus bund=
le ( link ). Jon will continue making YouTube videos, but transcripts and p=
odcast versions of his videos will be exclusively available to Stratechery =
Plus subscribers; you can elect to receive emails from Asianometry or add t=
he podcast to your podcast player on the Asianometry Passport site ( https:=
//asianometry.passport.online/member/ ).

I'm very excited about this addition; Jon is a great teacher about everythi=
ng from semiconductors ( https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3DPt9NEnWmyMo&list=
=3DPLKtxx9TnH76QY5FjmO3NaUkVJvTPN9Vmg ) and TSMC ( https://www.youtube.com/=
watch?v=3Dloiltpe6q-s&list=3DPLKtxx9TnH76SRC7ZbOu2Nsg5mC72fy-GZ ) to comput=
er history ( https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3DMgDZQy0nN-Y&list=3DPLKtxx9Tn=
H76QV56t5_ty1TDWQ2xmv75bs ) and company profiles ( https://www.youtube.com/=
watch?v=3DXQmXsbUYf9o&list=3DPLKtxx9TnH76Qod2z94xcDNV95_ItzIM-S ) , and non=
-tech topics like Taiwan ( https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3Dx02pq2HeKQY&li=
st=3DPLKtxx9TnH76Rxv5BOgJs_DHvlHxlcPhfo ) , China ( https://www.youtube.com=
/watch?v=3DaL_kzMlqgt4&list=3DPLKtxx9TnH76T_4R7Lxs8QoDr64zlvt8SS ) , Japan =
( https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3DK_0rF3OCxD0&list=3DPLKtxx9TnH76RTpIBp5W=
Gyun3Nn85sQxLK ) and more. There is an absolute wealth of information on hi=
s channel, which is very well-organized with extensive playlists ( https://=
www.youtube.com/@Asianometry/playlists ).

In this interview we discuss Jon's background and how he got started on You=
Tube, and then I ask him to teach all of us about how semiconductors are ma=
de. We cover all of the major steps in the process, and touch on the releva=
nt equipment makers and quite a bit of history. I learned a lot in this int=
erview, particularly about the importance of chemicals and Japan's dominanc=
e in that part of the process, and how TSMC works to spur competition among=
st semiconductor equipment makers.

